As a test sample, on the other hand, to be used after the GGSL-UNet has been trained to check the performance for application to real data, we will use the high-quality candidates of real strong gravitational lenses from the catalogs of (Petrillo et al., 2017, 2019a, 2019b) 222https://www.astro.rug.nl/lensesinkids/full_left.html and Li et al. (2020) derived from Fourth KiDS Data Release (DR4; Kuijken et al. 2019).
To select strong lens samples from KiDS, we follow two basic criteria. First, we keep the samples with the obvious structures of strong lensing cases, such as arcs or multiple images around the lens. Second, we select the cases matched with spectroscopic survey catalogs, such as SDSS (Bolton et al., 2012; Smee et al., 2013; Dawson et al., 2016), GAMA (Hill et al., 2011; Driver et al., 2011), and MUSE (Napolitano et al., 2020), which can provide precise spectroscopic redshifts (spec-z) for foreground galaxies. We finally identified 50 high-quality KiDS strong lens candidates, with their basic information shown in Table 1. This Table provides the 𝐵𝑃𝑍𝐵𝑃𝑍\it BPZitalic_BPZ (Benítez, 2000, 2011) photometric redshift estimates based on 9-band (u⁢g⁢r⁢i⁢Z⁢Y⁢J⁢H⁢KS𝑢𝑔𝑟𝑖𝑍𝑌𝐽𝐻subscript𝐾𝑆ugriZYJHK_{S}italic_u italic_g italic_r italic_i italic_Z italic_Y italic_J italic_H italic_K start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_S end_POSTSUBSCRIPT) photometric data from KiDS+VIKING, derived using the Gaussian Aperture and Photometry (GAaP; Kuijken 2008) flux method. It also lists the spectroscopic redshifts (spec-z) of the 50 candidates, obtained by matching to different spectroscopic surveys, in Table 1. The details of strong lensing analysis for the 50 cases will be presented in another paper (Luo et al. in prep) in the future. Here, we focus on the decoupling and photo-z estimation of foreground galaxies and arcs from background sources in this paper.

The aperture magnitude of the foreground and background sources are approximately calculated following Eq. 17.
In Fig. 16, we plot the foreground and background magnitudes, mfsubscript𝑚𝑓m_{f}italic_m start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_f end_POSTSUBSCRIPT and mbsubscript𝑚𝑏m_{b}italic_m start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_b end_POSTSUBSCRIPT, which are calculated using the reconstructed optical band flux F^fsubscript^𝐹𝑓\hat{F}_{f}over^ start_ARG italic_F end_ARG start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_f end_POSTSUBSCRIPT and F^bsubscript^𝐹𝑏\hat{F}_{b}over^ start_ARG italic_F end_ARG start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_b end_POSTSUBSCRIPT, versus the KiDS catalog magnitude, MAG_GAaP in Table 1. Here, we have corrected mfsubscript𝑚𝑓m_{f}italic_m start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_f end_POSTSUBSCRIPT and mbsubscript𝑚𝑏m_{b}italic_m start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_b end_POSTSUBSCRIPT for extinction, as has already been done for the KiDS catalog magnitudes (MAG_GAaP, see Kuijken et al. 2019).
The mbsubscript𝑚𝑏m_{b}italic_m start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_b end_POSTSUBSCRIPT is much larger than mfsubscript𝑚𝑓m_{f}italic_m start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_f end_POSTSUBSCRIPT, as expected, since most of the lens candidates in the dataset have lower flux compared to the foreground galaxy.
Considering that the foreground flux is difficult to distinguish from the background and noise when the flux is low, we have additionally applied a correction for the foreground, using the flux inside the 95% flux contour of F^fsubscript^𝐹𝑓\hat{F}_{f}over^ start_ARG italic_F end_ARG start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_f end_POSTSUBSCRIPT. One would expect mfsubscript𝑚𝑓m_{f}italic_m start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_f end_POSTSUBSCRIPT to approximate MAG_GAaP, but it is slightly larger in the u𝑢uitalic_u band.
As MAG_GAaP is derived from galaxy shapes and position angles, the GAaP method may not be able to distinguish between the lens and arcs in low SNR images, such as those in the u𝑢uitalic_u-band. Consequently, MAG_GAaP values for u𝑢uitalic_u-band images might include contributions from both the lens and the background galaxy.
Because the flux F^fsubscript^𝐹𝑓\hat{F}_{f}over^ start_ARG italic_F end_ARG start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_f end_POSTSUBSCRIPT only includes the flux of the foreground, we calculate the total flux of the foreground, F^fsubscript^𝐹𝑓\hat{F}_{f}over^ start_ARG italic_F end_ARG start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_f end_POSTSUBSCRIPT, and background, F^bsubscript^𝐹𝑏\hat{F}_{b}over^ start_ARG italic_F end_ARG start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_b end_POSTSUBSCRIPT. The magnitude is then calculated using Eq 17, and the results are shown in Fig. 17. The figure shows that the u𝑢uitalic_u-band matches better when considering both foreground and background flux, but the u𝑢uitalic_u-band magnitudes are still slightly overestimated in this case. Nonetheless, it demonstrates that the background image contributes a significant portion of the u𝑢uitalic_u-band flux. This is consistent with the physical scenario of the lens where the foreground galaxy is redder while the background is bluer.

The parameters for the foreground and the background Sérsic profiles are shown in Table 2. We used flat distributions for all parameters to avoid an unbalanced training sample and a realistic range of intrinsic parameters, as suggested from the real data (see, e.g., the BELL GALLERY, Shu et al. 2016).
As a first proof-of-concept test, in this paper, we cover a reasonable volume of the physical parameter space of the lensing systems, despite this might not fully consider all possible parameters, including extreme cases (for example, we are excluding very flat foreground systems with q∼0.2−0.3similar-to𝑞0.20.3q\sim 0.2-0.3italic_q ∼ 0.2 - 0.3). This option makes the network training more efficient, fast, and easier to converge while improving performance within the primary parameter space. Although the parameter space has been chosen to optimize the model training, the testing step in the following section shows that the GGSL-Unet still performs excellently in most mock/real lens test cases, as quantified by the chi-squares diagnostic.

The synthesis of the background galaxy will be sheared by large-scale external perturbations. This external shear is separated into two shear components, γ1subscript𝛾1\gamma_{1}italic_γ start_POSTSUBSCRIPT 1 end_POSTSUBSCRIPT and γ2subscript𝛾2\gamma_{2}italic_γ start_POSTSUBSCRIPT 2 end_POSTSUBSCRIPT, along the radial and tangential directions. The foreground and distorted background images are then convolved with a Gaussian Point Spread Function (PSF). For the KiDS-like lensing systems, we have adopted a constant σ=0.4′′𝜎superscript0.4′′\sigma=0.4^{\prime\prime}italic_σ = 0.4 start_POSTSUPERSCRIPT ′ ′ end_POSTSUPERSCRIPT, corresponding to an FWHM ∼0.7′′similar-toabsentsuperscript0.7′′\sim 0.7^{\prime\prime}∼ 0.7 start_POSTSUPERSCRIPT ′ ′ end_POSTSUPERSCRIPT, which is the average seeing for the r𝑟ritalic_r-band in KiDS and very close to the median seeing of the HQ strong lensing candidates in g𝑔gitalic_g- and i𝑖iitalic_i-band (∼0.8′′similar-toabsentsuperscript0.8′′\sim 0.8^{\prime\prime}∼ 0.8 start_POSTSUPERSCRIPT ′ ′ end_POSTSUPERSCRIPT)333To save computational resources and storage, we used the same mock parameters/templates across different bands, applying the same σ𝜎\sigmaitalic_σ for all bands. For instance, we only mock 1x64x64 Ifsubscript𝐼𝑓I_{f}italic_I start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_f end_POSTSUBSCRIPT and Ibsubscript𝐼𝑏I_{b}italic_I start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_b end_POSTSUBSCRIPT with the PSF applied and then adjust the parameters α𝛼\alphaitalic_α, β𝛽\betaitalic_β, γ𝛾\gammaitalic_γ, and ϵitalic-ϵ\epsilonitalic_ϵ to produce images for the four bands. This approach reduces storage and memory usage by 75%, which is beneficial when dealing with more bands (e.g., 9-band images) and large volumes of training data.. Note that for this first experiment, our choice to ignore the (albeit small) band-to-band seeing variation can potentially impact the accuracy of the GGSL-UNet in real applications where a band-to-band seeing variation might be rather common. As we will test the trained network on real observations in §2.2, we will keep this in mind as a possible source of systematics. However, we anticipate here that we will consider this implementation for future analyses (see §5).

We use U-Net to extract the different components of lens images.
The U-Net model is a type of generative model consisting of two main branches: down-sampling and up-sampling blocks with shortcuts at the same level. The down-sampling and up-sampling blocks mainly comprise ResNet structure units (He et al., 2015) and transformer structure units (Vaswani et al., 2017).
The down-sampling reduces the dimension of features, while the up-sampling increases them. In our case, this means reducing the image’s last two dimensions (see Eq. 5). For instance, the first down-sampling block in Table 3 reduces the input image size from 4×64×64464644\times 64\times 644 × 64 × 64 to 32×32×3232323232\times 32\times 3232 × 32 × 32).
We use the Python module diffusers 444https://pypi.org/project/diffusers/ (von Platen et al., 2022) to quickly build a U-Net model, in which the blocks and the channels used are shown in Table 3.
